A Republican strategy to oppose the re-election of Obama
The Republican leaders justify their policies with the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth by affirming that electoral fraud in the United States is rarer than the number of people killed by lightning.
The Republicans' lawyers, by the way, have recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the US in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on turnout.
In this sense, these measures partly undermine the democratic system of the USA.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for holding elections in the individual states.
In this sense, since 2009, the majority of American governments have announced new laws that make the registration or gang procedure more difficult.
This phenomenon became more important after the November 2010 elections, in which 675 new Republican representatives were registered in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws were introduced in 2011 alone, which restrict the exercise of the right to vote in 41 countries.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of US citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the periods of early voting, declare the right to register as voters on election day invalid, and deny citizens the right to vote for whom a court act is available.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. state asked voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
In 2008, the Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of the Indiana Law.
The Republican authorities hurried to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have promoted draft laws in 34 states that force voters to show a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
Indeed, 11% of US citizens, i.e. 21 million voters, do not have a photo ID issued by a government authority in their country.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an identity card.
However, often more than a hundred dollars are to be paid to get the necessary ID.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 do not have the necessary photo identification.
This is far more than that.
Students who are seen as voters who are increasingly voting for democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several countries.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs to vote more strongly for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs for elections.
Before 2004, no state requested proof of citizenship for voting.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws demanding voters to prove their US citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic voices.
For it is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the democratic party.
In addition, republican legislators have promoted laws in eight states in 2011 which abolished the registration of voters on election day.
In addition, you have restricted the right of individuals and groups to assist those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the campaign to register voters in the general elections in 2004 helped to register about 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the number of new voters' registrations by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, the Republican legislators have passed laws in five other states aimed at shortening the period for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 general elections in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, although they represent only 13% of the state's voters.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter represented only 11% of voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, the whites, who represented 76% of the voters, represented only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, the democratic legislators and their supporters have vigorously opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
Several draft laws were blocked by the veto of democratic governors.
The Advocate General of the United States intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote.
The democratic critics denounce the party-political nature of the passed laws and see them as a clear goal of influencing the results in the states that are decisive for 2012.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that those states that passed these laws make up 171 of the 270 votes required by the electoral committee to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes to electoral legislation will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on turnout.
In this sense, these measures partly undermine the democratic system of the USA.
