The Higgs boson analyzes
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused a certain stir last summer, and for good reason.
Indeed, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
Finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model - our best or "least false" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - but has not yet been empirically observed.
But for the physicists it is not yet completely certain that this is really the Higgs.
Without the shadow of a doubt, we know that we have a real new particle and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but there is still a lack of data to be completely certain about it.
Nevertheless, let us assume that this is actually the Higgs, since there seems to be only a small risk of being deceived, and let's look at what it is about.
There is an inevitable law in this world that causes two objects not to be present in the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and don't try too hard as you will hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law applies to them as well: the Pauli principle of exclusion, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantum state," whereby this "state" consists largely of some of their properties.
Based on this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and obey the Pauli principle like.
And in the other, the Bosons, an evil gang of anarchists, to whom nothing is sacred - certainly not this principle, which means that they can indeed be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are divided into two groups, according to the website The Particle Adventure from the Berkeley laboratories (which is absolutely amazing, by the way): the mesons that we will not treat here and the "particles of force" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
It must be emphasized here, however, that these bosons are not all as exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle" which is the "bote" of electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" at exactly this place, like a pebbles thrown into a pond.
This "disorder" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force."
More stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, has to be "disturbed" to show this boson.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, a little like a frozen pond, whose surface could only be furrowed by a very large rock.
Therefore, a huge particle accelerator such as CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, it is not all particles and not all materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don't - for example, a sheet of paper would never keep it in the refrigerator by itself.
And not all particles interact equally with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (as the photon, by the way) have no mass.
What can all these researches be "good" for now, asks Mrs. Plamondon?
For science, they are used to check the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to investigate all the deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
There are, by the way, numerous physicists who desperately hope that such deviations will be found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and plug some holes in the model.
It must be said that the latter still has great defects, since it does not provide an explanation for gravity (ups!) and dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the universe (erneut ups!).
However, such deviations have not been found in CERN so far.
Impact
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there is no one.
By the way: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell labs did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 - has already told us that the laser was more regarded as a "lab gaming" at the beginning.
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also result from all the instruments that surround the research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in optics in 1969.
Although it was not the original purpose, today this sensor serves all digital cameras worldwide as an "eye" and has won it the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this doesn't mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it means that you can really never know...
Palliative Care - The Best Way to Die... Le Devoir
With her Committee on Die in Dignity, Quebec recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate must be resumed shortly, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to look at this.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that raised him had given him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I managed seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed in the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
"However, it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it," he says.
The disease does its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he resigns and agrees to get help with the meal.
Courageously, he even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medication, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to heal my diarrhea, since it is humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"Over the course of our lives, we learn that a man is peeing standing up," says Pierre Brodeur, psychologist at the home of Victor-Gadbois.
Returning to the childhood phase is an unacceptable humiliation for certain persons.
"This depends on the ability of the person" to take a step backwards, he notes.
In the opinion of several people working in palliative care, great events take place in the midst of these regressions.
The patients who are admitted to the Home for Palliative Care Victor-Gadbois are all suffering from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, doctors and nurses taking care of them no longer overcrowd them with so-called "healing " care.
For Mrs. A., 89 years, the worst fear is to die "conscious and suffocated. "
But because of the illness, I really met my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I have no desires in life anymore," she says, before accepting that they put on a mask to help her breathe.
She still expects a last visit from her son, who comes from Italy, in the next few days.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois one offers with a group of volunteers body care and help with food intake.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more enjoyable.
In Quebec there is a bed for palliative care for 11,700 inhabitants.
That's very little considering that one day we're all going to die.
Here life is continued under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given oral care with Brandy or Pepsi, as desired.
The diabetics no longer have to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help relatives and patients alike," reports nurse Nathalie Savard.
Victor-Gadbois home isn't a day like the other.
In addition to an old man of 93 years, who enjoys the last family meeting in the courtyard and is well supported by his pillows, while in his honor, a young man of 36 years, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two little children, dies tragically after trying everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients less than 45 years of age," says Dr. Christiane Martel, worried.
53% of patients admitted to Victor-Gadbois' home come from their home, 47% from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their lives, both at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Home of Victor-Gadbois and the Society for Home Palliative Care in Greater Montreal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
Exactly this great deficiency in Quebec's health care ensures that several doctors specialised in palliative care are concerned about the adoption of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been circulating, signed by prominent figures in palliative care, such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's healthcare system is not efficient enough to ensure that everyone has the right to high-quality palliative care before accepting to go to euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days with great pain, without taking any measures to relieve her.
I'm afraid that the only reason patients want to die is because they don't get adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients despite the worst predictions until the last day.
The chances of Hélène Richard's survival were already minimal when she stopped chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop treatment, she replied that she regretted that I was giving up the fight, she told me.
However, she had told me that I was finished!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of the patients who have asked to die thank the nurses for not accepting this request after their pain has been alleviated by a palliative care team.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care for the Montreal area's home palliative care society, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
Thus, at the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which results in either sporadically or permanently sleeping the patient until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not alleviated all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean, "I want you to put me to sleep," but "I want my pain to be eased."
