Nothing particularly impressive compared to world trade in real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success," "in competition with the dollar or euro" and "similar to traditional currencies."
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as the "Credits" that are used to advance in a video game that you can win or buy (and sometimes exchange back) through games.
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, every time the trade is controlled and handled by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all net nodes are simultaneously custodians of the invoicing book, auditors, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of data related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can check the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are present in the public accounts' billbook spread throughout the network.
The decisive step is to enter this new transaction in this book.
This is done via a mathematical task that is started on the computers, whereby the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, has the privilege of adding this additional line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing is "hacked."
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
When this number has been found, the other nodes can effortlessly check if it is the right one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If one user wants to pay two times very quickly (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain without any link, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task receives 50 bitcoins.
In order to prevent inflation, this reward will be halved regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The Bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but can be divisible up to one hundred millionth, which leaves some room for manoeuvre...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with each improvement of the computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
The websites providing services to Bitcoin were attacked and the Bitcoin deposits stolen.
Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, who is a company to pay with real money and who uses the network Bitcoin, assures that "the vulnerability used does not concern the actual protocol."
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
However, cash also shows these shortcomings.
Important actors such as Wikipedia refuse to donate of this kind.
They are accepted by others like the WordPress blog platform.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the billing book and showed that almost 80% of the bitcoins are out of circulation.
A "mega-final sale" was launched in November.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book about this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its Paytunia system corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions that are thereby cheaper.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented by dealers, and the latter do not have to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just need to specify an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend in which hierarchical systems are rethought in favour of more horizontal systems.
"It will take some time for Bitcoin to prevail, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
The ECB's report, by the way, provides for the re-evaluation of the various risks now considered to be high in the event of this currency's success.
