A constitution with the crowbar in Egypt
It is a new poker game by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever with regard to the Constitutional Declaration, which temporarily grants it unlimited power of attorney, it has decided to put everything on one card.
To the surprise of everyone, he announced on Wednesday that the constituent assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had granted this assembly two additional months for the completion of its work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has been relying on a provisional text, which has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only led to an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president remains in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and" trample on justice. "
It is assured by its supporters that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time, which forces the brothers to renounce their intention to explain to the Egyptians the text section by section.
It is also a way for the President to regain his public and democratic legitimacy while the protest rages throughout the country.
Following confirmation in an interview with the American weekly magazine Time, Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote favourably.
When an ultimatum is placed on the Egyptian people with this retraction of a hasty vote: "Either you vote for my draft or I retain unlimited authority," the latter should supposedly end after the adoption of the Constitution.
85 largely Islamist members of this constituent assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of Liberals have not responded to the request.
Shortly before the Constitutional Declaration in mid-November, they turned away because they felt that they were unable to demonstrate their views.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
Yesterday morning 11 people, alternate members, were added in a hurry to achieve the quorum.
Some are very close to the Muslim brothers.
It is not surprising that the articles were usually adopted unanimously.
By the way, the commentators found it entertaining that the only difference of opinion of the day... was expressed in the time of prayer, since some members of the panel thought that the pendulum clock of the constituent assembly was not accurate.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Finally, Article 2, which drew all attention, remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of justice."
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules," which would have made a stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their good will and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
The liberals, who regard this only as propaganda, respond to "shyness."
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
In particular, they have an eye on Article 220, which grants the University of Al-Azhar a consultative role, in particular with regard to the verification of compliance with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people who are asked for an opinion have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy whatsoever.
One can see in this the first signs of a theocracy."
The fears of the liberals are also nourished by the fact that the next rector of this university is far less moderate than the present one.
"Currently, there is no concrete religious commitment.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics who have been partly trained in the French system," says Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He admits, however, that "there may be ambiguity in relation to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
It refers in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic case law, ed.]
And in the future, the question could be raised as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to decide."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticised for the far-reaching powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brothers argue that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention: the powers of the army.
In line with the military's wishes, the examination of the defence budget is not presented to Parliament but to a national defence council.
Similarly, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the associations for the defence of human rights have called for.
The latter also share their concerns about the text which they consider to be a threat to freedom.
The facts of blasphemy are being maintained and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Furthermore, no article refers to the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In their opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on TV last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The proponents of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel Ukrainian tourists expect sacred sites, the navel of the world and a sea from Sole
The Promised Land unites the glory of Bible truths, modern comfort and unspoilt nature.
AIF gives you the five most important reasons for visiting Israel.
Bend before the sacred places
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God's blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the transformation of water into wine at a wedding celebration, walking on the water, the closure of the sea storm and fishing.
Right here Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most sanctuaries, however, are found in Jerusalem.
Here believers make the path of suffering or the Way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress of Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the Old Town to the Church of the Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, where there is the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus.
Here, according to the Christian view, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands in the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
In Jerusalem there is also the most sacred place of the Jews - the mourning wall, the remains of a temple that was destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave notes with desires that then come true.
Take a Journey in the Heights
The ruins of the fortress of Massada form the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies that Herod the Great had built for his family in 25 AD.
They are located on a rock wall in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only climbers can reach the ruins of their own power.
All the others bring an aerial cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at 1600 to 2040 meters altitude there is the famous ski resort Hermon, in which it attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to one ancient legend, pagan gods lived on the top of the mountain.
Visit Unique Museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
Not all of them can be visited on only one trip.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be paid a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum near the Knesset (Parliament).
There, ancient Qumran manuscripts or Dead Sea scrolls found in rock caves in the Judean Desert are kept, as well as approximately 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
The collection of works by the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is exhibited there.
In Akko you can visit the museum in the Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of old Turkish baths with sculptures of the visitors and bath servants of the time.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures by Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are generally rejected.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most moving section is the monument to the children who were built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
There is total darkness when entering the room.
Stars are sparkling.
And the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died resound.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing Something for Health
The three most important recreational areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
At each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Amazingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature does not fall below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and there is bathed all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a location of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise water has a high salinity and thus even non-swimmers carry easily on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt brine) and medicinal mud, as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and for the calming of stressed nerves.
Touching the Mysteries of Ancientity
The old town of Tel Aviv, namely the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast, holds these secrets.
Through this city was the famous sea route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark right here, and Perseus saved here the beautiful Andromeda, with which he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow alleys named after zodiac signs.
According to the legend, Fortuna is supposed to be the hold of all those who touch the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa you can meet newlywed couples from all over Israel and even other countries at photo events.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can wander through the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and the residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
In the carefully restored theatre evening concerts and operas are performed today.
Bookmarks for tourists
When you go to Israel, don't worry about your poor English skills: about 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the trip is better not taken in Euros, but in Dollars, which can easily be changed into Shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you usually get ahead by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a high-speed tram and in Haifa the only metro line in the country with six stations connecting the suburb to the upper city.
Actually, it's an underground funicular.
A journey within the city costs 6 shekels, regardless of the mode of transport, including transfer for a journey of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturday.
From Friday night until sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport is suspended.
And on Sunday morning, the week of work begins.
In many cafés, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and food containing both milk and meat products.
Instead, you can choose between different dishes with mutton and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls of pureed beans and peas (falafel), as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this, there are many well-fed cats that stray through the streets comfortably and uninvited.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the rooftops of parking cars.
The cats like lively places and don't say no to treats.
A rental car costs between 37 dollars a day (Hyundai Getz) to 188 dollars (Audi A6, Volvo S80) depending on the brand.
The insurance costs an additional 15 dollars a day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels a day.
Tickets for museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
In figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreation seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118,8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, an increase of 51% compared to the same period in 2010, before the visa requirement was lifted on 9 February 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" leads to Moscow: Migrants Save Money for Language
While MPs and civil rights activists discuss the benefits of the law on binding language tests for migrants, criminals are already dealing with fake certificates
Every year 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the families remaining in their homeland.
On 1 December, a law came into force requiring every migrant worker to pass a test certifying knowledge of the Russian language.
Until now, this regime applies only to migrants who want to work in the service sector, in the municipal housing industry and in the retail trade.
However, the tests will become mandatory for all guest workers in the future, according to the Federal Migration Authority.
Not only language tests, but also tests in Russian history and the basics of legislation have to be carried out.
Language skills must be demonstrated for both receipt and extension of the work permit.
Exceptions only apply to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
This law also excludes persons who received their certificates and diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Sense, Problem and Protection of Rights
The whole of the examination centres will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian Language, the Russian University of People's Friendship, Moscow State University, Saint Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take the tests in all cities; more than 160 centres have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, asked the following question several times before the law came into force in the press: What does it actually bring?
What are the changes in the rule of language skills for both the Russians and the guest workers?
In particular, spokespersons from the Migration Authority said that the aim was to reduce the number of forced labourers.
"Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers," says Viktor Sebelev, head of the representation of the Federal Migration Agency in Tajikistan.
However, their rights must be protected from their departure.
Only an organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical assessment encounter problems.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions who will put him in a dark, narrow barracks under the pretext of help, where he will endure with dozens of his equal months without food and documents and work 12 to 14 hours a day.
We get many complaints from our migrants.
"In the homeland you are promised the One, and on arrival you will be deceived, their passports will be taken away and will not receive the promised salary," confirms Tolib Schwaripov, head of the head of the labour migration department of the Tajik Migration Agency.
Don't scold me, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to earn their money in Russia admit that they are not only unable to speak the language of the destination country, but also can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: only a few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford a reasonable primary education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As a teenager, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to earn money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists stress the following important aspect of the law.
Only migrants with legal status have to pass the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the guest workers continue to stay illegally in Russia.
"Welcome" or "no access to unauthorised persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to get an official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The staff of the Russian police know that our documents are mostly fake and we are not registered, and then there are cases of extortion.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," the Tajike Umed Hushkadamov comments to journalists.
"Just don't shy away from the costs of fake papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of migrants can be falsified.
Some fake certificates that certify the completion of the language test have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners didn't get it for nothing: every migrant who hoped to save himself the tests in this way paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: it costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The fact that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption, so that certificates cannot be bought simply, is agreed by both officials and civil rights activists.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test for the first time that they will have time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered jobs in areas where no active communication with people is necessary.
Interior Ministry ignores illegal arms market
The proportion of legal weapons in criminal offences is extremely low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior is planning to tighten up the weapons law for private arms owners.
The authorities are thus responding to recent events: wounded in shootings at weddings and seven dead in the amok run of Moscow lawyer Dmitri Vinogradov.
The police want to ban the use of non-dead weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by the Chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Corruption, Irina Jarovaja, and promised that the amendments to the Weapons Act would shortly be submitted to the Duma.
Not all of them are satisfied that the Russian authorities want to tackle the problems by "attacking the screws."
An open letter was published on the Internet, whose authors - representatives of various arms associations - demand that the authorities refrain from "sensual tightening up."
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very low, said the criminal, Vasily Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed over six months in 2012, while a total of 1,168 thousand offences were recorded for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that tightening up the law for private gun owners will not prevent criminals from serving on the black market.
At the moment, according to the authors, in Moscow you can find any weapon for little money.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior emphasizes that the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons reach the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, told a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a web page that accepts weapons orders
The first channel is the army or military, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," says Baranez.
On the second channel, there are illegal weapons stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that this includes weapons stolen from both the police's armory and directly from law enforcement staff.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons camps.
Explosions often occurred in many military camps.
"There is evidence that some cases were arson to cover up the lack of weapons," says the former military officer.
According to Baranez, weapons manufacturers also contribute to the black market.
"Today there are countless private arms factories that do not stand up to international competition and therefore throw the weapons under the hand on the black market, for example in Moscow," the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many pistols and rifles come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a separate, sometimes handicraft production and a mafia that organizes smuggling," explains the former military personnel.
Where did the guns come from?
Experts calculated the share of each of the five channels in the supply of illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was prepared by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Public Administration.
The experts analysed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminal literature and publicly accessible data on weapons portals.
According to investigators, the vast majority of illegal weapons come from the army and legal protection authorities.
Half of all weapons on the black market were there by "the debt of those responsible for their work with weapons, " says the report.
According to the researchers, 17% of weapons come from conflict areas, 14% from thefts in weapons production, and 5% from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant from a gun shop that does not want to be named assures that weapons found in illegal excavations have long been out of date and no one buys them.
According to him, it's more common for traders to get supplies in a weapons warehouse.
A gun, such as a TT gun, is purchased via an ensign.
The weapon is issued and passed through the fence.
"The dealer brings the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros per piece with two magazines," he says.
"The police know everything, of course, and therefore, if they cannot comply with the crime detection plan, they periodically buy controls from dealers who offer illegal weapons," adds the sales advisor.
"Like in the luxury store"
Buyers and sellers most often find one another through acquaintances.
I had looked at websites and blogs when someone came to my attention and suggested coming to the station "Begovaia" where a person would wait for me to take me to a certain place where we could then negotiate the price.
The price for the gun I only learned there
Military Commentator Viktor Baranez
"To get a gun, I need an acquaintance who has contacts," says the sales consultant. "I have such an acquaintance, but I don't trust him."
There are traders in the markets, but there you have to go and arrange for a code like "by Ivan Ivanovich, who lets you tell him that the daughter has lost a tooth."
At the moment, I even get a few rings about a friend I trust.
