"The brain is only moderately outwitted"
The theme of extended reality, popular with modern technology fans, is usually perceived recently by the lens of a special pair of glasses.
At first Google presented a working model at its annual conference in the summer, and in November it became known that Microsoft had also applied for a patent.
However, in conversation with the head of the Interactive 3D Technology Group at the Microsoft Laboratory in Cambridge Shahram Izadi, it becomes clear that the glasses were only a passing station for the company's scientists.
It stimulates the possibility of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands and creating virtual open spaces.
- Please describe briefly what research your group is doing.
- We deal with the interaction of man and machine, but want to extend the limits of this interaction.
So far, mankind has largely remained stuck in the phase of working with pixels on flat screens, which are sometimes also touched.
However, we want to look 5-10 years ahead and anticipate the radical changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are progressing, and nowadays no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in motion control.
- What else awaits us in the future?
- Although Kinect has brought the interaction to a physical level, much is still happening on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system receives more data) has been improved, the output is not yet decisive.
We try to change this, work on real three-dimensional display systems based on different technologies, including projections.
We need to release the computer world into our physical world and make it more tangible.
For this, however, it is necessary that not only the user but also his environment is recognized.
Then we could add virtual objects to the real world much easier.
And first of all, we should get rid of these stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
She's popular, but isn't she overrated?
- It is certainly not the all-purpose solution, as it raises questions about privacy, because one does not always want to inform all those around about his actions and intentions.
Actually, any kind of interaction with computers is good, but each in its particular niche.
For example, in the area of controlling objects in public places, we worked on a project in which we experimented with short and scarce gestures instead of exploding gestures.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but could theoretically be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, the future belongs to mixed control types, such as gestures and language.
- How?
For example, would you ask me to give you this bubble can?
They say it and point it at the same time.
- I usually just say it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to see.
- Does that mean you want the user to adapt to what a machine can and can't afford at the time?
Not necessarily, but it's about a mutual approach.
I think that in the near future we will have to work above all on the development of new sensor types, which will enable us to better understand people's reactions.
These can be laser sensors, for example, as they offer good resolution at depth, which is very important.
- What are your demands on modern cameras based on your work with the Xbox Kinect sensors?
Is there a lack of resolution, depth, or anything else?
- The present generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 megapixels with a speed of 1000 fps wouldn't be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
From this point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us, as the developers of the algorithms have more work.
Not only the resolution along the X- and Y-, but also along the Z-axis must be taken into account.
The speed and the number of images per second are also important.
The movements of man are extremely dynamic and frankly said, the current 30 fps are too little especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes developed a contact sensor in our Redmond laboratory with a adjustable processing delay of between 1 and 100 milliseconds, with today's commercial sensors closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction between man and machine.
For my work, I needed just such a device, without touch control and with more images per second.
- Shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
- Kinect currently works with three "cameras," one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the other a receiver for the reflected signal.
