It is not used to calculate the object depth.
More cameras could possibly solve the problem...
Or amplify the problem, as more calculations would be necessary.
It would be nice to have a flexible Kinect-like system, in which we could play with different camera inclinations to see how this helps us in the three-dimensional determination of a position.
- If I remember correctly, Microsoft, unlike Google, didn't present his glasses to the public.
Do you not think that with regard to the application of the technology of extended reality in everyday life the glasses have the best prospects?
- Of course, it's not pleasant to always hold a smartphone in the raised hand while on the go, but I think the most amazing option would be a "changing" extended reality, in which we could switch from glasses to the smartphone via a cloud,
The glasses are a personal gadget and that's their strength (privates can only see you), but at the same time their weakness, because an extended reality by means of glasses prevents you from working together with others on virtual objects.
- Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is not only accessible to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to normal mortals.
There is a problem that critics often point to: there is no tangible reaction!
The hands don't feel anything!
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
- In my lectures, I often talk about the fact that the enlarged reality represents the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth breakthrough could well be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method is currently the use of the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection document.
She's taking great pressure!
But there are also technologies that are actually designed to give the "images in the air" something firm, for example, the interference of some directed ultrasound rays at a certain point, where the finger is, creates a feeling that is currently as weak as someone coughed over the handballs.
There are also braces for the wrist that affect the nerve endings in the fingers, which is also a potential direction.
- Did you try to outwit the brain?
Make it think it feels what it should feel when it's seeing something?
- That's a good idea. We haven't tried it yet.
Here is another task that we will have to struggle with for a long time, namely to let a person who is physically in a closed room believe he is instead in an open, practically infinite space; here we are working on concepts with treadmills (others than in gyms), mobile platforms and large spheres.
So far, the brain is only moderately outwitted, and there are many years of work ahead of us.
This is precisely what makes working in the field of virtual reality so attractive for a researcher: on many topics we are only at the beginning.
