NKÚ boss: Black system control fails due to political fault
In connection with public contracts, the Czech Republic has good supervisory authorities and adequate laws, but falls behind in their application.
Speaking for Aktuálně.cz, Miloslav Kala, Vice President of the Supreme Control Office (Nejvyšší kontrolní úřad, NKÚ).
"A law is never perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and I do not think this is the case with us," Kala comments on the current situation.
A similar result appears to be a joint control by Czech and German auditors.
As a negative example of practice, he cites the attitude of Prime Minister Petr Nečas to the so-called "black system."
Recently, the Prime Minister said that ODS would not harass entrepreneurs with controls - is the system now banned or allowed?
"A law must be valid, and if something is forbidden by law, then the chairman of the government cannot simply come, and the control office, whose duty is to control compliance with the law, hinders its activity," Kala notes.
At the meeting of the Supervisory Committee of the Chamber of Deputies, you spoke about a joint Czech-German project comparing the laws of both countries on public contracts.
What was that about?
This is a parallel test that we started about two years ago.
Simply put, it is a question of the European legislation defining how public contracts should be managed, and that is what national legislation is based on, and finally, there is the actual practical application.
We have all compared this with each other, and although the examination has not yet been completed, we have found extremely interesting differences. Generally speaking, the laws are perhaps even more "stricter and perfect," but the actual application is better in Germany in some parameters.
This confirms that it is not enough to establish new and more precise rules over and over again. It is also necessary to deal with the actual application of the law.
How can the project help you? What is the result of this project?
It is precisely this kind of joint control that could help us to stop constantly trying to perfect the laws and reduce and adjust thresholds if this does not seem to have a particularly positive effect.
Efficiency means buying a thing at a reasonable price (which is not always the lowest price) and excluding unlawful enrichment or even criminal acts.
But reducing thresholds for contracts does not guarantee that we will achieve this goal.
Perhaps it is even the case that in this way we only burden the system with excessive "paperwork," and those who are looking for gaps in the system have it much easier to exploit the system than if the thresholds remained higher.
They are talking about the problems in the practical implementation of the Czech Procurement Act.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there a similar authority here as our NKÚ, or does the system work differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the German counterpart to the NKÚ is the Bundesrechnungshof, which is similar to ours and also has a college, which is only formed slightly differently. Basically, however, both authorities work similarly.
The competences are also comparable to a certain extent, but Germany is a federal state, i.e. there are also these courts of account in the individual federal states - in this the German system differs from ours.
The BRH is only allowed to control federal funds, which corresponds to our state resources.
Public funds, which are managed by the districts and municipalities, are subject to the control of the state accounts.
As far as German legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would hate to compare this without specific information. Nevertheless, in some respects Germany is often referred to as a model, but it is certainly not possible to say that Germany is better in everything.
Is that perhaps because the examiners are better there?
This is certainly not, but as I said: I do not like such comparisons very much.
It should also be noted that those countries that are an example for us are also facing problems.
Otherwise, they wouldn't have had any cooperation with our authority, would they?
As far as Czech legislation is concerned, what importance did the amendment of the procurement law have for your authority, do you already feel any impact?
Considering that this amendment is only in force for a short time, it does not yet have an effect on our trials.
Since our controls are carried out subsequently, there is a certain delay to be expected here.
To date, we are more likely to have an impact in the preparation phase of future controls - we have introduced the new control instrument "Recognizing risks of inefficiency" and are examining and analysing almost 14,000 public contracts with it - where the changes will naturally have an impact, as the thresholds are changing, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, among others.
Do you think the adoption of this law is rather positive, or will the system be burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think that this law is definitely a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption will be confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "stricter" and can no longer be respected.
Under the previous rules, the persons under examination are already accountable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational programme of regional policy, the Regional Council) to ensure that any non-compliance with the Procurement Act is equivalent to a breach of budgetary discipline.
But does it make sense to make the law even stricter?
I do not think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system and not punish those who have committed a formal error that does not affect the actual decision-making process.
Such a system puts even greater pressure on bureaucracy.
Where's the way out?
First of all, let's say which path is not effective.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS would not bother the entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called "black system" - what exactly does that mean?
Is the black system now forbidden or allowed?
A law must be valid, and if something is forbidden by law, then the chairman of the government cannot simply come, and the supervisory office, whose duty is to control compliance with the law, can hinder its activities.
He can say, "We change the law and allow the thing," but he can't say that we're pretending to be nothing.
The Procurement Act contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain operations - and this is also correct for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, however, it is also tragic if the bidder with the best offer is excluded solely on the basis of formal errors.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and that is what I think is missing from us.
