Šimon Ornest: At our concerts we want to gather positive energy
What do you think is going to happen in less than a month?
This is one of those disaster reports that we people like to start at.
With our band The Tap Tap we make fun of it and say that we are the only band in the world that can collect enough positive energy to stop or prevent the world's end.
In December you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
It's a nationwide benefit event that we've been planning for two years.
To this end, we want to use the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, which is expected to end on 21 December at 11:10 a.m.
On the day before, i.e. on 20 December, three concerts will take place in Prague, Brno and Ostrava at 21:00.
The end of the concerts is supposed to be about the time when the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which lies in a time zone around 12 hours ahead of us.
Who made this idea?
Originally probably from me, then we designed the idea together with our graphic designer Honza Augusta.
In doing so, we not only want to gather enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think together with the public about the state in which we are once handing this world over to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, t-shirts, bags and keychains against the end of the world, with which people can also support us through www.e-tap.cz.
The band The Tap Tap has also recorded together with other performers the so-called anthem against the end of the world with the title "World Doom Falls Off."
The anthem on YouTube is already very popular today. Will it also be heard at the charity concerts?
Of course, and at the very end, provided that everything works out and that the end of the world doesn't happen...
The anthem is to be sung by all performers on all three concerts at the same time.
In addition, the hymns are broadcast live together in a direct connection from Czech television.
The hymn's lyrics are by Tomáš Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, Xindl X also sings with...
How did you get to work with both of them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we realize many charity events and concerts...
We strive to involve these people intensively in our projects.
It turned out that most people are interested in working with us and have fun.
What is the purpose of the proceeds of the concerts against the end of the world?
For the establishment of the barrier-free educational center Studeo, which we have already been working on for six years together with the association Tap at the Jedlička Institute.
The students of the Jedlička Institute are regularly supervised by lecturers who help them with different leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the lecturers, we would like to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a separate building is to be built in which we will then move in with this project.
Several groups and performers perform at each concert.
What criteria did you choose them for?
We wanted to put together a programme that appeals to all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý perform.
You can find everything else on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "large events" planned for the future?
In May we perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, and for this concert we prepare an interesting programme with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are already in the USA - would like to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not very small, so far you have already appeared in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap, however, is a group composed of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these journeys logistically and organizationally?
It's not as bad as it seems at first sight.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs must be transported in the luggage compartment. We also have to carry many instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked without problems, ČSA and British Airways have always been very well prepared for us, that sometimes I have wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
By travelling abroad, you have a comparison of what it looks like in the individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people there, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities, where everything works better than ours, we witnessed in Russia that everything is still in its beginnings in the East.
Opposite Prague, Moscow is absolutely not accessible for disabled people. It is still unusual there when someone is alone in a wheelchair in the city centre.
It is not even self-evident that you leave a wheelchair user in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also associations that try to point out the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what way do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There's a lot of things we're gonna hang out with...
It should be noted, however, that improving the situation always depends on the efforts of those concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public spaces, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
But it is not exactly common for a larger group of disabled people to actively participate in social events there, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect for the public and accessibility is one thing, but only when important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only isolated cases of particularly strong personalities.
The Tap Tap is very popular at the moment, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time, I started as a supervisor at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in getting involved with something intense.
And since I am a musician myself and play saxophone, I founded a music company together with a colleague.
Well, and in time, as our presenter, Láďa Angelovič, says, something has gotten out of control (laughs).
But didn't the band become known until the last few years, or am I wrong?
It is true that working with well-known singers helped us; we also started to actively promote ourselves.
We have become aware that if you do something and you can't see it to the outside, your performance doesn't exist in a sense.
Thanks to EU funding, we can also afford good editors, high-quality equipment and so on.
Was it your goal to get this far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt the potential that you can handle things differently.
In the show business today, one often copies the other.
This is logical in its own way, since everything new is viewed with caution and only accepted after a long time.
There are only a few really unique things, and I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression that the viewer usually has is, of course, compassion; that's only natural...
But this compassion is absolutely superfluous, because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we should regret.
They are people who can live and develop a full-fledged life, provided they have the means to do so.
I always say that if people with disabilities succeed, this is not only for them but for society as a whole.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as one hears from many people?
If one wants to do something well, one must not compromise on many things and must also demand some discipline.
However, I believe that this is perfectly normal.
Some come to us with romantic performances, and when they find out that they have twice a week rehearsals, have to complete preparatory phases and spend a lot of time on concert tours, the enthusiasm with many quickly disappears.
But that's how it works everywhere, in every band that really wants to work and achieve something.
Currently, The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of them were there from the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
Only one: Láďa Angelovič.
We're an open group, people come and go.
Who has the will and the desire to participate is always welcome with us.
