Poland and space.
Last week Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of this space agency at a Council of Ministers meeting of the member states of the European Space Agency ESA. Poland is thus the second member of the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland's way into space began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts were engaged in space travel, although they did not always get an understanding of it.
I recall here, for example, the lecture by A. Šternfeld on 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Eingang zur Kosmonautik."
However, the ideas of the young engineer (b. 1905) left the audience cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, donated by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for "Eingang zur Kosmonautik."
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's worldwide recognized contribution to the development of space travel was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the earthward side of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925 a railroad draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket propulsion was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used for starting or braking the draisine.
The information on this matter comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-powered missiles.
The research was carried out by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
It can be seen from the documents that have been handed down that research has progressed to the stage of practical tests.
The research was then interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937 the technical press published the design of a photoelectric hunting rocket by Ing. Rohoziński, and in the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of rocket propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukovy).
The committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of work, its work ended from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space travel appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Agency (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this society was made in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles are devoted to space travel.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for the creation of a space company.
At that time there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was foreseeable that exploration of space would have a future.
As early as 1956, the Polish space company PTA sought to join the International Federation of Space, which was founded in 1951, and indeed the PTA became a full member in the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA Chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Vice-Chairman of the International Federation of Space.
He held this post until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flying height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh quite 5 kg.
Later an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 flight tests began in the Błędów Desert with the two-stage rocket RM-2.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
A further development stage should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach a flight altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of vertical winds.
In 1962, however, the further development was discontinued.
The first RM rocket was built in 1962 and was replaced by the Meteor 1 rocket.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed of this rocket (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) which differed in size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport room with 0.4 liters capacity, Meteor-1B over 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C over 0.62 liters.
The maximum altitude for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the aviation institute, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were then built.
Poland's accession to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 is also worth mentioning, followed two years later by the establishment of a national COSPAR Committee.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites as part of the Interkosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Hermaszewski became second intercosmonaut after the Czech Republic Vladimír Remek.
