The movie Argo: If it's the worst, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of protesting Islamist students occupied the US Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the overthrown Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the USA after the revolution, who had maintained the patronage of his regime for decades.
There was no positive way out of this situation for the American government - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have severely damaged the confidence of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to enforce the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a heavy blow to the reputation of the united states, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt to release the hostage made everything worse.
The imprisoned diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been arranged by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages caused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments at home.
The debacle in Iran greatly contributed to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by the director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story, which gave the USA a small partial victory.
Six embassy staff managed to escape immediately before the embassy was occupied.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring refugees from Iran, helping them with an extravagant story to cover up their true identity - they traveled with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film staff who allegedly visited locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by the expert on "exfiltration," Tony Mendez, also required the collaboration of Hollywood.
For the cover to become credible, articles on this film project appeared in professional journals, press conferences were held, and the fictitious production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have been kept secret for a long time, based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic politthriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie," i.e. the story of a successful Hussar piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
As a result, the mood levels in the film alternate - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and there are no major differences in the film version of the same situations).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which come ironically and slightly exaggerated.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, in the hallways, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has succeeded in a remarkable restart of his career with this film.
A smiled actor has become a respectable director, and as an actor he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the crime novel Kein Kinderspiel (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the thriller city without mercy (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film, which doesn't play in the director's native Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that removed the previous films of this director from the standard Hollywoods.
However, Affleck also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film are played in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that really took place - the opening sequence of the storming of the message is very impressive in its clarity, yet conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictable that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team have a similar effect on fictional scenes (the wrong film stick on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story doesn't actually offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
But with the little he works quite successfully, sometimes helping the reality a little - which then does not always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the impending crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted by a telephone call in America, or also the chase on the runway, seem something artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its too wide dispersion, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters deserve more space, and thus they are far from alone in the film.
As a result, Affleck's film loses a bit of traction. It is a film that you can follow with a certain interest and at the same time gout the design and the retro style reminiscent of a thriller from the 70th years.
However, it is difficult to arouse enthusiasm.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history still alive in a certain way and as proof of how exaggerated the ideas of the almighty and omniscient secret services are, it is sufficient.
Guidelines for the inflation of balloons, bananas and the circus
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which annually calls out a survey on the most absurd bank fees, has decided this year to organize the competition "The most absurd regulation or idea from the EU workshop."
"This idea was inspired by the EU's recent plan to introduce a 40% women's quota in the management of large European companies," said Patrik Nacher, who is responsible for organising this survey, to the newspaper Právo.
Among the nominated absurdities, for example, is the judgment of the European Court of Justice on the harmonisation of insurance tariffs for men and women.
Until then, women enjoyed an advantage in life insurance because they objectively represent a lower risk for insurance companies.
"Further incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be nominated by the end of this year.
The actual vote will then take place until the end of February 2013," said Nacher.
The controversial EU regulations include, among other things, the mandatory incorporation of bioethanol into fuels, which as a result is damaging to nature, and the ban on reliable mercury thermometers, simply because they contain a relatively small amount of this dangerous substance, or the directive on the size of chicken cages, which made eggs considerably more expensive this year.
In the past, criticism has also been expressed about the actual ban on the use of the term "butter spread" or the ban on the sale of conventional light bulbs.
Bananas must be 14 cm long
The EU apparatus often decides under the pressure of this or that lobby of trade and industry, whose demands are usually represented in Brussels by one or more Member States (for example, the Czech Republic is currently trying to enforce the demands of Czech banks by veto threat).
Lobby interests were also behind the fact that bananas of the highest trade class in the EU must be at least 14 cm long and must not have "curvature anomaly."
The European Commission defended itself with the argument that it merely harmonises the inconsistent national standards that would hinder trade.
Fruit and vegetable standards have already been softened by the EU against the opposition of some countries, indicating that the existing directives would lead to a waste of food.
A candidate for the victory in this survey may be the EU regulation of last year, which, according to balloons, must be provided with the indication that children under the age of eight cannot inflate the balloon without the supervision of an adult.
The EU referred to an American study that, according to balloons, is the leading cause of child suffocation.
A similar restriction applies to children up to 14 years of age when using fairgrounds.
Curious ideas are also available at home
Relatively absurd is also a directive that concerns European officials themselves - anyone who has an official role in the EU must not use the name Macedonia because of the sensitivity of the issue for Greece and must instead say FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
The Bankovnípoplatky.com server, in cooperation with the Association of Liberal Economists Laissez Faire, nominated not only the aforementioned absurdities but also the EU regulation on the volume of food stocks in the territory of a Member State.
The EU thus determined the maximum volume of food stocks that could be in the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the EU.
The Czech Republic then exceeded, for example, the fixed volume for preserved mushrooms, for which we were threatened with a high fine.
The survey organisers were also impressed by the idea that certain countries should receive money for not having a sea, or the idea of giving funding for applications for funding.
These ideas, of course, did not come from Brussels, but from Prague.
"We are disadvantaged by the fact that we have no sea.
We will apply for reimbursement from the EU," said Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD), then Minister of Agriculture, in the autumn of 2004.
As an argument, he argued that the grain harvest was very high and that the state camps were overcrowded as a result of the so-called intervention purchases.
As the Czech Republic has another way to sea ports, according to Palas, the EU should pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
The European Commission finally approached the Czech Republic so far that it organised an invitation to tender for the purchase of cereals from countries that do not have access to the sea.
The Ministry of Regional Development, headed by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), offered funding for applications for funding to the municipalities, in particular for funding applications to Brussels.
EU: Bizarre regulations are the exception
While regulations are easily the target of criticism in the Member States, some experts believe that the EU's efforts to regulate and thus to promote the effectiveness and development of the whole European Union deserve more recognition.
According to these experts, a more serious problem is the EU funding for projects which have nothing at all in common with the deepening of European integration, but which have been forced by individual Member States in the budget negotiations.
Emotions in this country also evoke the fact that the Czech Republic, like other Member States in Brussels, has to fight for the right to use specific designations of traditional products and does not always win this fight.
Although the Czech Republic was able to defend the name "Olomoucké tvarůžky" after a six-year struggle with Germany and Austria, the Inländerrum (Tuzemský rum), whose tradition dates back to the 19th century, our manufacturers had to rename it "Tuzemák."
Rum may only be used for sugar cane distillate products, not for sugar beet products.
In the official list of products registered in the EU, the company of world-famous cheeses Feta and Gorgonzola, Lübeck marzipan or Parma ham now also includes Karlovy Vary Zwieback, carp from Pohořelice and Třeboň, or Saaz hops.
With an EU brand, the Pardubic gingerbread or the Hořicer rolls can boast.
