And Stefan Spermon, IT technician in a nearby large company, says, "Yes, it's nice, the house."
But I wonder what we need a library for today.
All have internet, iPad and e-books.
No one's going to one of those old-style libraries today, is it?
Spijkenisse, a sleepy town at the gates of Rotterdam, is a remarkable record holder.
The 80,000 inhabitants community has the lowest educational rate in the Netherlands as a whole.
In order to counteract this stupid circumstance, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to the general formation and to recreate the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the Euroscheins as beautifully brushed reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there is only one way to master statistics: a library must come!
Winy Maas from the Rotterdam architectural firm MVRDV, master of the cool bar diagrams and producer of funny, often cynical buildings, took the matter with familiar serenity and appeared for the competition hearing in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin in his face.
And while the jury was still looking around and shrugging with the armpits, the cheeky Maas stacked his exquisite souvenirs of greatness to a pyramid and finished his actionist speech with the words: "Dear city council!"
So this is it, my proposal for the Bücherberg of Spijkenisse, for the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain is filled up.
It is part of a revitalization project, which includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Bücherberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012."
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, the faceless small town resort, which up to now had no more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a stunned ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory in order to richer a piece of contemporary architecture.
Above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The Long Way to the Book
The first impression: Büchereldorado under cheese bell.
Although there is a lift that leads through the middle of the mountain massif, the true pleasures of space and reading open up when climbing the topography on foot.
The all-round glazed interior is bright and clear, the burnt clinker floor and the elegant street lanterns speak the language of a public city square.
The urban ambience is perfect.
You're already looking for park bench, dog and football-playing boys and girls.
And books, books, books everywhere.
"The bookshelves usually stand along the façade, and in the middle there is a large, dark room, which is usually uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic room configuration upside down and put the reading area from inside to outside.
The interior of the Bücherberg is skilfully used: offices, internet library, chess club, environmental center and house technology center are located in the center.
A special pleasure are the black bookshelves, which are sometimes wall cladding, sometimes balustrade, sometimes stair railings.
Optics, haptic and smell are foreign.
Even die-hard architects and civil engineers shake the head of the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work here with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, at the request of the standard.
And so one day we encountered a suitable waste product from agriculture in a Frisian farm.
For many years in the Netherlands, a millimeter thin plastic fleece has been used as a root base in greenhouses and fields.
That's cheap and time-efficient.
The thin textile lasts one or two seasons, after which it is ripe for bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece - for the first time in these quantities - was pressed to four centimetres thick plates.
Under heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, load-resistant material that smells like a bit of new cars and a bit of a sports shoe.
After 105 steps you arrive at the summit.
At the end of the nearly 500-metre-long walk, the Literaturcafé rewards you not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and potted ficus trees.
They provide atmosphere, but above all for the correct humidity in the literature mountains.
Donations for the New Soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but despite the many glass surfaces, this house is a showcase project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
Heated and cooled with geothermal heat.
Although the Bücherberg is under a glass fall, even on sunny days the sun shines only briefly inside.
The broad wood glue binders, which stand across the glass façade, serve as shade and capture a large part of the sun's radiation.
The indoor climate is very pleasant.
The rest do fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptics from the IT industry, already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And also the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even calls the Boekenberg Spijkenisses "the recently overdue soul."
The reason: For the opening a few weeks ago, every resident was invited to donate a book from his personal inventory.
For the time being, the optical gaps in the not yet fully equipped library - currently 70,000 pieces - are to be filled.
The concept has been established.
The shelves are filled to the top.
"Nothing is worse than a semi-empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I think, thanks to our invitation, every inhabitant now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
And if it's just for adornment.
Thus MVRDV has succeeded in the supreme discipline, which is called in the jargon identity foundation.
Spijkenisse wrote literary history.
As young and uneducated as she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-European relations, Berlin is balancing it on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany had initially signalled that it would vote against the request for Palestinian observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be careful because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to setting up a no-fly zone.
This was finally enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is currently changing its foreign policy away from a policy managed by the US, so to speak, towards a German foreign policy.
What is more, Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
So the Germans find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still touching on their role, but they are on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy like that of France or Great Britain.
What does a "normal" foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It shows the willingness to take positions in national interests that are independent of those of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain degree different from those of the other great powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the attitude of the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf states.
Therefore, it must be careful not to push the public, but also the elites, to the head in the Arab countries.
That definitely matters.
But I wouldn't want to put too much weight on that either, that's not a totally unilateral relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the US by abstaining from important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that there is a great understanding of the German position in Europe and even in the USA.
That is why I do not believe that this was such a dramatic break as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even have some respect for it.
Because it signals that it must be taken seriously as an international player and that its interests must be taken into account.
There are different opinions on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
The US, on the other hand, has clearly advocated a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European nations?
Because of American domestic politics, these differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama government has in secret quite a lot of understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, publicly represent this position.
I believe that the actual differences of opinion are not as great as they always appear.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not so enthusiastic about Netanyahu's politics.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand, and the position of the main partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would, of course, be a bit easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, which is not currently the case.
So they can't be part of a broader line and have to push things out of their own position instead.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take a leading role in pushing Europe into a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, even because of its relationship with Israel.
That has always been a sensitive subject.
But I believe that the Germans understand that they must play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself in the role of an important international player - does Germany even want to play a leading role?
Or does Germany still have a difficult leadership role?
Germany is not yet used to it, which is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a greater role.
For example, when we look at the euro crisis, every time Germany takes on a greater role, various anti-German feelings become free.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
This is actually the old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this sense, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the US.
It must be receptive to various neighbors and opinions and that is not easy.
Now the US's influence in European politics is steadily decreasing, but the EU is not filling this vacuum at the moment, who else remains?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, it's unpleasant to them and makes them even more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute in which academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly research the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
