Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most important sexually transmitted diseases?
The bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and tripper (gonorrhea).
Common viral STIs are HIV, human pappilomavirus, herpes genitalis or hepatitis.
Felt lice and scabies belong to the parasitic STI.
Who are the main groups concerned?
Syphilis and trippers are especially common in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four out of five of all cases of syphilis reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomonads, candidiasis (fungus), tripper and human papilomavirus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The prevalence of HIV among heterosexual adults in this country is comparatively low - nevertheless, this group accounts for around 20 percent of new HIV infections.
Chlamydia infections are much more common among adolescents than in other groups of the population.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In addition, human papilomavirus are common in adolescents in this country.
How has the number of infections developed?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to reporting.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections more than doubled from 1697 diseases in 2001 to 3698 diseases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has decreased since 2007.
In 2011, there were around 2700 cases.
That's about a tenth less than the year before.
What symptoms indicate venereal disease?
The infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort during urinating, discharge, abdominal pain as well as blisters or warts.
Often, however, they do not cause pain or other symptoms and therefore remain unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of contagion, but do not provide 100% protection.
In part, pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be passed on through lubrication infections and close body contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examinations, especially with frequently changing sex partners.
Early diagnosis of most STIs can be cured and late consequences avoided.
