Mexico's Enrique Pena Nieto is facing a difficult start
While Mexico's future president Enrique Pena Nieto is preparing to take office, Will Grant from the BBC analyses the challenges ahead and the mixed feelings of his people.
Currently, traffic in Mexico City is particularly poor.
Even on better days, this is always a clogged city, but on Monday a ring of steel was built, which blocks off several important traffic routes to the capital and creates chaos on the streets.
The aim, however, was not to disturb commuters on their way to work, but to prevent demonstrators from reaching Parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico's new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidential bond and take over the leadership of the nation.
He's facing a complex task.
Under the outgoing government of Felipe Calderon, Mexico has been able to prove itself economically well, but the country is under the control of a drug war that has already cost 60,000 lives in the last six years.
"My government is strongly committed to reducing violence," Pena Nieto told US President Barack Obama in the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy with which we can achieve this goal.
Before joining the US President, Pena Nieto served as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, extensive part of the country surrounding the capital, opinions about the new head of state are divided.
A Direct Man
In the remote small town of Valle del Bravo, for example, one likes to remember him.
Residents of the resort attribute to him the development of tourism and the development of infrastructure.
To reach the city, one can drive on one of the highways that Pena Nieto had built and which represent a great improvement over the brittle, bumpy roads that once existed here.
Plaquets with its name also hang outside a modern sports center and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect from him real and lasting changes," says his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who works as a congressman for the Pena Nietos party, the PRI.
In particular, as far as security and the economy are concerned, we hope for an interesting and real change that our country needs so much.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the Presidential Palace of Los Pinos, the party has great expectations of Enrique Pena Nieto.
He rejects the opposition's allegations, the new president's lack of substance.
He is a very direct man, very committed and has big plans for the country.
He is an outstanding statesman, but above all he is also someone who can listen.
But on the other side of the state, not many people share this view of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the paved streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
The town is hidden under highway crossings and in many ways represents a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are of crucial urban nature.
Earlier this year, the military was engaged to fight drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
In the last two years alone, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left on a patch of wasteland near a large landfill.
