There were signs that she was beaten, and the morgue had already been deployed.
As her mother tells her story, a picture of Mariana looks down on us from the wall. It is placed next to a cross that bears a single word: justice.
But this, according to the family, has been denied to her until now.
The authorities treated me as if I was a chatter, a troublemaker, a moustache.
They want you to just accept their verdict and keep your mouth shut.
"But this is not possible if there were so many formal errors and omissions," she says.
When President Pena Nieto receives the President's bond on Saturday, he also takes on a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have been affected by violent crimes over the past six years, and the new president has promised to deal with this problem in particular during his term of office.
"I hope that as president he is the same as he was governor," says PRI Congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But that is exactly what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza are most afraid of.
The prosecution claims that Bradley Manning did not complain about abuse
The prosecution contradicts Bradley Manning's allegations that he has been mistreated in prison
The hearing deals with Manning's time in the military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defense seeks to dismiss the indictment on the grounds of harsh prison conditions
The U.S. Army Private is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents
On Friday, the prosecutor's office tried to find that Army Private Bradley Manning - accused of the greatest disclosure of confidential information in US history - failed to complain about the alleged abuse he suffered in military custody.
During a cross-examination of Manning during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein explained that documents relating to weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning's nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia had no complaints about his treatment.
One day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a request by the defense to dismiss the charge - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the hard term - Manning had testified that he had considered suicide in prison.
The U.S. Army intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The material was then published on the Internet by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks never confirmed Manning as a source of information.
In the hearing on Friday, Fein went through with Manning the forms that officials had filled out after their meeting with Manning during his detention in Quantico Military Prison, where he had been in prison under increased detention conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein asked him about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had judged the treatment by his guards as "excellent" and that the treatment by the institution as a whole was "very professional."
The forms, according to Fein, did not contain any complaints about maltreatment, even though the officials had asked Manning directly about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and that the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they were dealing with them. However, they had not been logged.
"They wrote down "no problems" (after discussing the concerns), and that did not necessarily mean that I didn't say anything at all," says Manning.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he didn't complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicidal ideation he mentioned a few months earlier on a form.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to reduce his observation status to "prevention of injuries."
The military claimed that it had assigned this restrictive status - one level under the threat of suicide - to it and to the protection of others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well and to get rid of the observation status for the prevention of injuries (...) in order to achieve a higher quality of life in my view," said Manning.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest and transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the Quantico Naval Base prison in Virginia in July 2010.
He said that in Kuwait he had considered suicide and had become unconscious due to the heat.
Not knowing what was happening to him or to the outside world was incriminating.
"My world shrunk at Camp Arafjon, on this cage," Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was gonna die in that cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell - at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours - and without company.
They only allowed him a mattress, a blanket, flip flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he was trying to keep moving, because the day was forbidden to sleep or even to lie down.
He always had to sleep with light that penetrated his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and guards couldn't see his face, they woke him up to turn back.
Manning's lawyer formally objected to Manning's treatment in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the Fort Leavenworth, Kansas Military Prison.
On Friday, the judge also asked Manning about an accusation he had made in his statement on Thursday - so he had to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico for one night and stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners on a morning count.
Manning had testified that during this count he had never had the opportunity to envelop himself with his blanket.
During the interview on Friday, Manning stated that he had concluded from an order from his guard that he should drop the blanket with which he could have covered himself. However, he admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday, Manning had testified that he was forced to sleep naked the previous night. He had previously tried to show an official that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning told the official that he could have used the waistband of his underwear or his flip-flops to hurt himself, but did not.
That night, Manning said, his underwear, flip-flops and glasses were removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his prison experiences and drastically reduce his detention if he is sentenced to trial before the military court, which is scheduled for early next year.
The defense has indicated that Manning will plead guilty of lesser offences, while other charges that are considered too extreme are to be challenged.
Continuation of the hearing is scheduled for this weekend. The prosecutor's office is expected to justify the terms of detention.
The Pentagon remains in its position that Manning has been held in accordance with the provisions applicable to all prisoners held under the highest security precautions in Quantico.
Charges against Manning include the favoring of the enemy, unlawful publication of intelligence on the Internet, the transmission of national defence information and the theft of public property or documents.
If he is found guilty on all counts, he is threatened with a life sentence.
My Mexican-American identity crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to accuse the emigrants - they remind them of difficult times, he says
Navarrette believes that Mexican Americans are caught between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed the hall and arrived at the passport check when perplexity spread inside me.
Signs referred to two queues: one for "Mexicans" ("Mexicans"), another for "Extranjeros" ("Ausländer").
I stood there for a few seconds, insecure, to which I should go.
I grew up in Central California and was called "Mexicans" all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation - just as my friends in Boston call themselves "Iren" or my friends in New York "Italian."
Later, I chose "Mexican-American."
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather's homeland, there was no need for abbreviations or hyphens.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, at least good enough to assert myself in this language at both ends of an interview.
But I don't have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I don't get rid of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and put myself in line for Extranjeros.
I was thinking about that moment this week when future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet President Obama.
On the agenda were all the topics that are expected when the heads of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy. It is one reason why Mexicans today are just as likely to stay in Mexico instead of emigrated to the United States.
He wants to join forces with the United States and Canada and create a North American trading bloc modelled on the European Union.
And Pena Nieto swore to continue the war of Mexico against the drug cartels, even though he didn't mention any details.
Mexico's relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought on the United States coming to Mexico in 1848 and forcing the country's leadership under a gun to leave more than half of its territory to them.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries and not minutes, memories of this event cannot be overlooked.
So as soon as a U.S. government official makes even the mildest criticism of Mexico, complaints are heard - in the Mexican press and among the country's elites - about how the Americans oppress the sovereignty of their neighboring country.
And the children of Montezuma go on the warpath.
And yet Mexico's biggest challenge is in fact in relation to the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about resentment?
There's more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers. People for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason why so many people of Mexican origin live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that at one point in our family tree a person - perhaps a parent or grandparent - was offered no chance in Mexico and emigrated to the north.
And in most cases this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our faithfulness is with them.
Not Mexico.
And although we may have now lived the American dream, attended good schools and received good jobs, we must never lose sight of the American dream we are living - not the Mexican dream.
Our identity may sometimes be blurred, but as far as our loyalty is concerned, this is not the case.
This clearly applies to the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many members of the Mexican leadership do not like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our gang to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
And then we wouldn't be caught behind the silk curtain - with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there are tensions between Mexicans and Mexicans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are - and Mexican Americans resent this.
While she is an American citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know feel that they are not one country or the other.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You enjoy the best of both worlds, but none of them are rooted in them.
In Mexico, we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we're seen as Mexicans.
As I should learn during my trip, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: some Mexican leaders and parts of the educational bourgeoisie want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as temporary "ambassadors" for Mexico, who represent their interests in the United States.
We should tell our American colleagues how great a visit to this country is and put pressure on the political leadership to intensify their ties with Mexico.
Well.
That's not gonna happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And given the unfair distribution of income, unbridled corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure whether this is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through it alone, Amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not ready to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans have a grudge for how their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmm.
Maybe we're more Mexican than I thought.
