Even if the Islamists, now in power in Egypt and in other countries, have little left for Israel, they will initially focus on the difficulties in their own country.
Israel's defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors together.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments to repair their economy.
The fact that pragmatic President Morsi met Barack Obama to reach a ceasefire could be a promising sign - and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis, too, should think longer.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking timid steps towards democratization, Palestinians continue to be deprived of their right to self-determination - a powder keg that will undoubtedly one day explode in the Israeli occupied territories, just as a bus in Tel Aviv exploded this week.
The oppression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population this situation will only worsen.
Bloody missions to repress Hamas in Gaza will increasingly demand diplomatic tribute over the years.
