Australian uniform cigarette packaging laws enter into force
Health warnings and diseased body parts on neutral green packs that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world's first laws for uniform cigarette and tobacco packaging have come into force in Australia, replacing brand logos and colours with neutral olive-green lids, which are also printed with drastic images showing sick body parts and babies and children suffering from cigarette smoke.
Apart from the different health warnings and pictures, there will be the only difference between the packs in the brand names printed in identical, small font from Saturday onwards.
Australia is thus introducing the world's most stringent regulations for tobacco packaging.
The Australian federal government wants to discourage young people from smoking by eliminating the glamorous image of tobacco consumption.
The government is based on studies that have shown that people who have not yet started smoking at 26 are not likely to start smoking at 99% after that.
"You can already see in children of young age that they understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to promote with their brand image," says Federal Minister of Health Tanya Plibersek. She cites studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will only have a minor impact on the profits of multinational corporations, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
It was said that the laws would favour the black market trade, leading to cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
"The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences," says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer far larger quantities of these products on Australia's streets.
Others, on the other hand, say that the laws have stimulated their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family-owned company, notes that the demand for cigarette cases and silicone lids to cover the unbearable packaging has increased enormously since British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco failed two months ago at the Supreme Court of Australia to challenge the laws.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale stores and is waiting for new stocks.
It's a good deal for us.
According to experts, the catch in the popularity of social media lies with exactly the population group to which the plan is directed.
A number of Australian laws have banned tobacco companies from TV advertising, prohibited them from acting as sports sponsors, and forced most traders to stop designing cigarettes in shops. Now tobacco advertising has switched to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned Internet advertising by local companies and sites, but has no influence on international sites.
"Whoever markets tobacco and has only one small area left to advertise its products doesn't come around the Internet," says Becky Freeman, health researcher at the University of Sydney.
On social media such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook, Freeman has noted an increase in experience reports on brands written by "all normal people."
You have to ask yourself the question: is this just a private person who finds so much pleasure in Marlboro cigarettes that she even records a video for it - or does a marketing agency have to do with it?
British American Tobacco Australia says that instead of marketing, industry is focused on dealing with the new laws.
It has even gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules - those countries complain to the World Trade Organisation about unfair trade restrictions, although none of the countries are trading more with Australia.
A WTO decision is expected for mid-2013.
According to Plibersek, the government has had talks with other countries that are considering similar packaging laws.
Canada was the first country to provide photographic warnings in 2001.
These have now been extended to more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Harder laws are being considered in Great Britain, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
