The house walls Pompejis adorns a Latin graffiti about boredom, which dates back to the first century.
And then there's the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at York University, Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After a long reading of research literature and the presentation of the idea in front of a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues concluded that boredom can be defined as the experience of "wanting to do a satisfactory job but not being able to do it."
Boredom therefore differs from apathy to the fact that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
In apathy, on the other hand, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, consists in "disturbing the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and feeling that time is only slowly passing away."
Boredom can sound almost like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that although these two conditions may be related, bored people see the problem in their environment or the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're bored, even if we're just having trouble concentrating.
In her study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - in German, for example: "The idle mind: the definition of boredom under the aspect of attention," which appeared in September in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a volume in which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud television program from the neighboring room, which had nothing to do with the content. Others heard it at low volume, so it was barely perceptible, while the third group did not hear these noises at all.
The people who heard the barely audible television said they were bored more than the other two groups - they had problems concentrating, could find no reason for them and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
When you try to focus on a difficult or strenuous task, the disturbance of attention can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
If, on the other hand, one does a monotonous job - "like the search for faulty products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help not to feel bored."
In fact, he says, we now know that zapping and scribbling, often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can even fight them by keeping people physically more attentive.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to hack around learn more and keep more information than those who are forced to sit still," Professor Fenske said.
We all get bored at some point - my late flight, a roaring loudspeaker, a particularly tiring film.
But some people get bored more easily than others.
In order to measure these differences, researchers developed a "scale of boredom susceptibility" in the 1980s.
On the scale there are statements like "Many things I have to do repeat themselves and are monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything."
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys get bored more often than girls, according to Stephen Vodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of West Florida - especially as regards the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a pretty tight bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32% of the adolescents were bored at school and doing homework, while 23% said they were bored when they were not in school.
But only 3% of parents said they felt bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he doesn't know whether the percentages of boredom have increased or decreased.
However, he is sure that "young people are perceived as particularly boring," mainly because children and teenagers do not have much influence on their everyday routine.
So back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases it leads to people taking extreme physical risks and falling into gambling or drugs to alleviate them - studies have shown that.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors examine the relationship between boredom and creativity. Professor Vodanovich is of this opinion, who has been researching the topic for more than two decades.
"With boredom, the brain wants to tell you that you should do something else," says Gary Marcus, professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn't always know what to do best right now.
If you're bored and you use this energy to play and cook guitar, you'll be happy.
But television can make you feel lucky in the short term, but these vanish in the long run.
So if you're going to give your bored child an iPad, you can get rid of boredom. However, it hasn't learned to talk or control yourself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: "Self-control transfers from one situation to another."
The child not only learns to talk, but also receives more self - control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we see them too critically.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable away from constant activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we need to be bored more often. But boredom is the tormenting, incessant desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that in truth, people are only looking for a way to shut down and relax.
"In an environment in which we are constantly overstimulated, it is difficult to deal with when the noise is silent."
