This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by getting sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
For this purpose, it must descend to the bottom of its crater every day, where the sulphurous gas emitted from the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulfur stones, which can weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the sloping paths of stone.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2386 meters, but the exhausted beams take more than 40 minutes to ascend at the turtle's pace, keeping the balance and carefully setting their steps so that they do not slip and fall.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed years ago on the steep slopes of Kawah Ijen.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 Eurocents for every kilo of sulphur they break down.
