The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, who has been exploiting the deposits in the volcano since 1960 and (never better) its workers to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Eurocent) for each kilo of sulphur.
This is then sold to the petrochemical industry for 10,000 rupees (83 Eurocent) each, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for the bleaching of sugar.
"As we normally carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each way," explains Anto, who normally makes three routes a day.
