We knew that the government had tried a lot, such as the marketing of perfumes with pheromones or the organization of speed dating evenings (fast flirts).
It is possible that many of these ideas were creative, but they did not necessarily lead to success.
So we thought: Why don't we do something as creative as possible to address this problem, such as composing a rap?
1.2 Children
Whoever does not take this issue easy is the Singapore government.
Each year, it spends $1,300 on policy measures to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for married couples and parents grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But everything has had little success so far.
Singapore is a rich, high-tech city state in southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its rulers and its strict social controls.
According to its National Population Authority, the birth rate is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time this rate was above 2 - which is also known as the replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why don't the Singaporeans have kids anymore?
Tan Wei Ming, Director of Marriage and Family Policy of the National Population Authority, says that this is due to "better education" and "greater career opportunities."
"This has enabled people to have much more options in terms of life goals and priorities, except to get married and form a family," she explains.
These changes in social conditions have contributed to the increase in the number of single persons and the delay in marriage and births, the result of which is a reduction in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at a drastic increase in immigration to counter the reduction of the population led to resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites where the barely laminated xenophobia blooms against many new immigrants, especially the Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and not integrating.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the Singapore ruling party achieved its worst election result since independence last year.
Since the elections, an attempt has been made to correct the problem with higher contributions and levies for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the falling birth rate has the known impact on a nation's economic growth, tax revenues, health costs and immigration policies, Singapore's example also shows unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to achieve that not so many small apartments are being built.
It already has an impact on the housing market.
The Urban Development Authority has begun to control the number of small apartments known as "shoeshoes" and allowed to be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have a living area of 46 square meters and show a great sales success.
However, there is concern that they can promote the lifestyle of the single, and that they discourage the construction companies from building large homes for families.
But Lim Yew Soon, general manager of the real estate company EL Developers, says that his "shoe boxes" can be sold much faster than larger housing units.
They are so popular, and the units are sold out days and even weeks faster than the larger housing units.
This means that they are much better for our cash flow.
He admits, however, that the new standards give the developers clearer orientations, which were previously put obstacles in the way if they wanted to build too many small housing units within a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city state.
Even if these new rules could pave the way for an increase in the national birth rate, talks with the Singaporeans working in the financial district show that they will not have much effect.
"People are very stressed out, the apartments and also the education are expensive, which is why it is postponed by many," says a young manager.
The children can have others.
"It is important for me to have my own money and time," says another man, about twenty years old.
Men and women cite their careers, the stress and the cost of ownership and education as reasons why they cannot have children.
That is why the Singaporeans have the last word when it comes to having children - there is still so much the government can do.
The offline private offline is private online
Privacy
According to the dictionary, this is the property of private or "that area of private life where one is entitled to protection from any kind of interference. "
What's private for someone under 16?
How is this definition applied to everyday life and social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he poses when he makes known on the Internet situations that he would not share in real life?
El Periódico interviewed five young people between the ages of 10 and 15 who are often on the net.
In four of the cases, they linked the term to "something very own" on a personal level and "to the password and the user" when they applied it to the social networks.
"My deepest secrets I wouldn't post," says the 10-year-old Jorge trying to explain the meaning of "private" in websites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"These are very confidential secrets, my mother may know them, but not the whole world," he confirms.
On FB I upload beautiful pictures or pictures of games.
I also spend my time with acquaintances.
"I wouldn't share a photo that isn't mine, or someone who makes the fool," he says.
The boy is aware that it is wrong to publish obscene photos, of naked people, of crimes, or to write insulting or violent comments.
Jorge claims to know 35 friends he has in FB and nine followers in Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Including the mother who has the password to one of the accounts.
I signed in to Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if anyone answers me, I just upload them," he adds.
"The social networks are entertaining, I can quickly talk to relatives in the distance or with friends," he says.
Asked he answers that he would never accept an invitation from an unknown.
Even if someone suggested a stranger to him, he would ignore it.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has user accounts in Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask. In Ask, he admits not to know 20 of the people he has added to his list of friends.
"That doesn't scare me, because we have something in common, for example music," he says.
According to the boy, no one gave him any hints or asked him for his address or telephone number.
"If someone pushes me or demands it from me, I simply remove it from my user account," he admits.
José contacted Ask after reading a recommendation in Twitter.
The boy is not unaware of experiences known today as cyberbullying.
A friend's acquaintance was blackmailed on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never knew who it was," he assures.
According to José, the victim didn't close the user account.
"He only did it privately."
Afterwards, he explains a number of steps to securely configure a user account.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yeah, I'd do that if he wasn't nice to me or I wanted to wipe him out.
"But I know this is cyberbullying," he explains.
Key questions
Marielos Porras, a teacher of English with a university degree in education and learning, believes that in order to orient the children and young people, it must be understood that it is the purpose of social networks to inform.
"The Internet was created as a medium for searching for information, but with the appearance of these pages the rules of the game have changed," she says.
Porras explains that the academic Marc Prensky, who holds a master's degree in pedagogy at Yale University and author of the work "Digital Natives and Immigrants," formed these terms to explain the phenomenon.
The digital natives are they, the children and young people who grew up with this technology.
"We are the digital immigrants they are supposed to teach, when we are still learning," he says.
He explains that this is a complex issue, "because we require them to have a defined criterion on what can be disseminated, published or said, at an age where maturity is not sufficient."
"They should also be selective, if they care about being popular, having thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences," he adds.
According to the skilled person, the most effective way to teach children and young people what privacy is is to ask them questions that make them think.
"To tell them not to do it, doesn't work," he says.
Porras then mentions a few possibilities: There are things you wouldn't tell a stranger. Why do you do it on the Internet?
Or, would you like to publish a photo of you, like the one you published from a friend?
Do you know what the others are publishing about you?
Did you ask the other people for permission if you labeled photos of celebrations?
And one more question: must everyone know what you are doing at any moment?
Another point is to give them an understanding that they need to act online as they do offline.
They're the same rules.
"Someone outside the Internet acts with respect, morality and other principles, and the same must apply to social networks," he explains.
Monitoring
Estuardo Guardia, university professor, primary school teacher and educator, comments that it is essential that parents carefully read the guidelines of social networks.
When they understand all sections, they have solid foundations to talk to their children about the importance of opening a user account on the Internet.
"For example, age, or what you can share or publish," he explains.
According to Guardia, the children must be reminded of the lesson "You must not speak to strangers."
Completion of Unasur Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and was theoretically to be signed by the seven leaders present.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the VI Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of the Unasur. Sources at the State and Presidential Chancellery initially announced that they would hand it over after the exam, but subsequently stated that it would be published at some time on the Peruvian Government's website.
When asked about the text, they stated that the content was presented to the press by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala.
Journalists' access to information on the summit was limited at all times.
During the day in the press room only the image of the President's meeting without sound was transmitted with the message "private session, limited audio."
The few information circulating among journalists was received from the press spokespersons of some of the Unasur governments present at the meeting, but not from the Peruvian press spokesman.
The only document that was distributed during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from different national and international media who demanded more information.
Afterwards, the Presidential Office of Peru sent the media an e-mail with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was Humala's declaration and not the official document at the end of the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South America - Arab States (ASPA), and on this occasion, despite the press's urging, the so-called declaration of Lima, which had previously been announced, was also not published.
On the official website of the ASPA you can be sure that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that the information systems were available to journalists, but they limited access to information to a large extent.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Hague Court of Justice, which settles a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the IGH, which begins Monday in The Hague, in the trial that Lima initiated against Santiago, to listen to the pleas of both sides.
"We will follow and execute the judgment on the differences we are currently making to this international court," said Humala together with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has been, is and remains a country that adheres to international laws, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and submits to international courts," adds Piñera, greeting Humala with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
Both presidents confirmed that they would submit to the IGH after Colombia had brought an action against the Bogotá Agreement following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which considered it a serious mistake, in which it agreed to submit to the judgments of that international court.
The summit was attended by the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from the Unassur since 2011 after the resignation of its President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and finished the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The head of state read the final document, in which it announced that 16 decisions were taken and the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries were set for a total investment of 17 billion dollars.
On the decisions taken, he said that the Unassur countries will "take significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, to which we extend the decisions on residence rights."
He stated that measures were being taken to "improve cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and organised transnational crime, as well as measures to improve access to medicines and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters."
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take on a triumphant trait, but should serve to expand our production performance and show our peoples a better future," Humala added.
"We have decided to give priority to a number of 31 emblematic projects designed to improve spatial links in South America, especially in rural and border areas... and thus unite our countries and open up new forms of economic activity," said the Peruvian President in a recited statement.
Among these projects would also be five Peruvians located on the transverse axes of its territory from the coast to Brazil, two of which would provide a better connection with Ecuador, although it did not provide any further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve for its resumption in the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to continue to be an integrated region for prosperity and peace and good neighbourly relations was another aspect highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before starting his participation in the regional meeting that on Saturday in Mexico he expected a meeting with his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, in order to treat the maritime conflict respectfully according to an IGH ruling challenged by Bogotá.
"Maybe I will meet President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)," Santos said.
"We will examine all these ways - they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua also requires talks with Nicaragua," he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilised and respectful as possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet on Saturday in Mexico, where they intend to be present at the inauguration of the new president of this country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the Block's Defence Ministers also met in advance to adopt the 2013 Action Plan, which aims to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru is presided over during the period of the regional bloc.
"South America must learn to integrate its citizens," says Rafael Correa.
The President of Ecuador, Rafael Correa, today confirmed that the creation of a common citizenship is a goal, with "South America actually learning something from Europe."
Correa, who took part in the 6th Summit of Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) held in Lima, told Peru's state television that Europeans "were killed in World War II and other conflicts" and "are practically a homeland today."
