And when Sweden interrogated Mr. Assange at the Embassy of Ecuador in London or Skype, as the Swedish case law allows and in other cases was done, the problem was solved.
Correa took the opportunity to confirm himself as a defender of freedom of the press and said that what he did not tolerate is "the mediocrity, the evil intention, and the lie that disproves freedom of expression."
"The greatest enemies of freedom of the press are not the evil and perverse politicians, but bad journalists who strive for profit and blackmail," he said.
In this sense, he congratulated himself on the fact that Ecuador is no longer dominated by such journalists "and not by bankers or hegemonic and petty bourgeois countries," and anticipated that in a re-election, he would "deepen the revolution in order to continue the path in this right direction."
Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto against Paraguay in the Unassur until at least its next elections, arguing that the organism "must remain hard and must not stand up to opportunism and no coup d'état disguised as legally" because it "destroyed the legitimacy of democracy in Paraguay."
Moreover, the President of Ecuador considers the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, now, and according to the judgment of the International Court of Justice of The Hague, which preferred the maritime sovereignty of Nicaragua to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime borders between the two countries, "absolutely entitled."
At present, this judgment is not being implemented.
It is a problem between a South American and a Central American state.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome in the pursuit of a common path.
They must be dealt with comprehensively so that they can be overcome and looked forward.
He also trusted in the same Court of Justice for a good conclusion of disputes over the maritime borders between Peru and Chile, and said that "it is right for Latin America to appeal to international authorities if both countries commit themselves to taking the verdict, even if it is very hard."
With regard to the possibility that he will stand as a candidate for the next presidential election in Ecuador in order to achieve his third mandate in a row, he stated that he sees this opportunity "with a lot of optimism and joy, although sometimes it is very difficult."
Correa assured that if he lost the elections in February 2013, he would withdraw from political life.
I have never personally been interested in power, but under such unfair circumstances as in Ecuador, this socio-economic poverty can only be corrected by political power.
"My political movement had the belief that it was I who guaranteed this probable victory, so I have to live up to this responsibility," he said.
If I were to win, it would be my last period as President, after which I withdraw from public life.
This also applies if we lose.
"That's decided," he explained.
Correa also referred to the treatment of the health problems of the president of Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, in Cuba.
I just spoke to the Vice President of Venezuela, Nicolás Maduro, who told me that he had travelled there for scheduled routine treatment and that he would be expected to return to Cuba after the election campaign.
"It does not mean a relapse in President Chávez's health," he commented.
