The cause of death due to AIDS today is too late detection
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed with the results of the study: HIV positive.
"It was as if a bomb hit," he says about the moment he received the diagnosis that the doctor tried to "weaken down" without any noticeable success.
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to learn about it; and this with such commitment that he was celebrating his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients of the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), in which he came after several fights in 1994.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, which was hard to imagine at the beginning of the 1990s when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigmata.
At that time, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye "because it led to a dead end."
At that time, AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome with quality of life.
However, many people still come to the clinic who know nothing about their disease and where the virus has already caused damage and exhausted their immune system, and who are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, i.e. after the first reported cases, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient taking up treatment in time and the survival of the general population are exactly the same," said the head of the HCG's HIV unit, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, saying that this information was supported by a prestigious scientific publication in April of this year.
The expert on infectious diseases and HIV/AIDS, Andrade Villanueva, commented that since 2008 the scientists have concluded that AIDS is not a death sentence, but that the years of survival and quality of life depended on the degree of impairment of the immune system of people at the start of treatment, and that those who are not addicted to drugs have greater chances: up to 30 years with a count of 200 CD4 and 50 years with a count of 500 CD4.
Simply put, the above statements mean that those who receive HIV-positive diagnosis at the age of 25 can, in this sense, "easily age 75 as long as they are under control," said this expert.
In order to properly classify this progress, it must be remembered that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Even if mortality has decreased significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has decreased from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (ONUSIDA's annual report), it is nevertheless true that 60 percent of the patients recorded in the national database have died since AIDS appeared.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and 187 deaths by May of this year; however, it is assured that universal access to antiretroviral medicines has been available since 2005.
- So why are people still dying of it?
In my opinion, the problem is not access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and so is in our hospital.
At least in the past 12 years, we have had no medical supply problems. The problem is that people come in a very advanced state because they do not know their state of infection, i.e. in very late stages of the disease.
He makes a striking statement: "Nine out of ten patients come to us if they already have an accompanying infection. In order to influence global mortality, more early diagnosis is required, which is why all persons who need it must be offered massive detection tests."
This proposal is supported by the experts and officials of the Consejo Estatal de Prevención del Sida en Jalisco (Coesida) (State Committee on the Prevention of AIDS in Jalisco) and also by the patients such as Fabrizio, who had his test carried out at a private laboratory, for the only reason that he had made a friend of his who, despite his young age, was already in the AIDS phase and even had the Kaposi sarcoma (a cancerous tumour), which is one of the usual complications.
Everything's different when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they're gonna die, and they don't want to hear anything.
"If I have to die, I prefer to burst three times," they say in my case.
The change was to improve, I eat well, exercise and take the medication.
Today, his parents only know that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, like everyone else.
"I work, do a lot, have an active but responsible sex life, I pay attention to my health and that of the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimate details with MILENIO JALISCO in order to animate with his testimony those who are now afraid in the context of the worldwide AIDS day.
They should take the test if they are part of the risk group. The sooner they know if they are HIV-positive, the better, and if they already know the diagnosis, they should learn how to live responsibly like all people.
His message is a summary of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There are big holes between the health programs and the ordinary citizen, Ricardo Salazar, journalist from Guadalajara, who has taken on the cause of HIV.
And the most important thing is prevention.
In the designated places "the distribution of condoms was actually increased; earlier they were delivered individually, now they give us packages with a hundred pieces, which is already good, but there are still people who do not have access to a condom," he said.
Among the risk persons for new infections are adolescents.
"What do you need them for?" is a common mockery of social workers, oriental staff in schools, employees in pharmacies and the health care system that young people do not want to expose themselves to, the correspondent assured.
He proposed that this inefficient distribution should be reoriented; the condoms should not only be located behind the counter, but also in output equipment in public toilets of institutions often visited by young people.
It is not intended to promote promiscuity.
They are not to be paid for the beer and motel, as Governor Emilio González replied to the question as to whether he would distribute the praesidium under his administration.
"Sexuality does not look like this; it is best to bring the condoms closer to those who are already engaged in sexual activity," he put it to the point.
Key Data from Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
Nationally, the state is in fourth place in new and cumulative AIDS cases, and in 13th place in relation to HIV.
92% of the contagion cases are by sexual intercourse, 6% by blood and 2% by perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV because there are 4 or 5 people who do not know for each registered case.
